In this activity, I explored how Terraform automatically loads variable files ending with:

```text 
.auto.tfvars
```

and how these files override values from:

* `terraform.tfvars`
* other lower-priority variable sources

The main objective of this activity was to understand:

* Terraform variable precedence
* automatic variable loading behavior
* variable-level overriding concept

One important observation during this activity was:

> Terraform does not override configuration at the entire file level.
> The overriding happens at the individual variable level.

This means Terraform evaluates variables one by one and replaces only the matching variable values based on precedence order.

---

# Created File

File: `prod.auto.tfvars`

```hcl id="yr3r1w"
insta_details = {
  vol_siz    = 60
  vol_typ    = "sc1"
  insta_deta = "t3.micro"
}
extra_tags = {
  Name = "Own-terra-auto-tfvars"
}
```

---

# Why `.auto.tfvars` is Important

Terraform automatically loads:

* `terraform.tfvars`
* `*.auto.tfvars`

without explicitly passing them from the command line.

So unlike:

```bash
terraform plan -var-file="prod.terraform.tfvars"
```

the following file gets loaded automatically:

```text
prod.auto.tfvars
```

This is useful when:

* default environment configuration should load automatically
* manual `-var-file` passing should be avoided
* environment automation is required

---

# Variable Override Behavior

Suppose the following value already exists in:

File: `dev.terraform.tfvars`

```hcl id="ndmjlwm"
insta_details = {
  vol_siz    = 40
  vol_typ    = "gp2"
  insta_deta = "t3.small"
}

extra_tags = {
  Name = "Own-terra-tfvars"
}
```

Now Terraform additionally loads:

```text
prod.auto.tfvars
```

which contains:

```hcl id="3tmjlwm"
insta_details = {
  vol_siz    = 60
  vol_typ    = "sc1"
  insta_deta = "t3.micro"
}

extra_tags = {
  Name = "Own-terra-auto-tfvars"
}
```

Terraform will finally use:

```hcl id="5ihnly"
insta_details = {
  vol_siz    = 60
  vol_typ    = "sc1"
  insta_deta = "t3.micro"
}

extra_tags = {
  Name = "Own-terra-auto-tfvars"
}
```

because values from:

* `prod.auto.tfvars`

have higher precedence than:

* `terraform.tfvars`

---

# Important Learning

The override happens:

* variable by variable
* not file by file

This is a very important Terraform behavior.

Terraform does not think like:

> "Replace the entire dev file with prod file"

Instead, Terraform evaluates:

* `insta_details`
* `extra_tags`

individually.

Whichever variable gets the higher-priority value replaces the lower-priority value.

---

# Example of Partial Override Concept

Suppose:

File: `terraform.tfvars`

```hcl
insta_details = {
  vol_siz    = 20
  vol_typ    = "gp2"
  insta_deta = "t3.small"
}

extra_tags = {
  Name = "Dev"
}
```

and `prod.auto.tfvars` contains only:

```hcl
extra_tags = {
  Name = "Production"
}
```

Then:

* `extra_tags` gets overridden
* `insta_details` still comes from `terraform.tfvars`

This proves:

* overriding occurs at variable level
* not entire file replacement level

---

# Terraform Variable Loading Priority

Terraform generally follows this order:

| Priority | Source                           |
| -------- | -------------------------------- |
| Highest  | `-var` command line              |
| Higher   | `-var-file`                      |
| Higher   | `*.auto.tfvars`                  |
| Lower    | `terraform.tfvars`               |
| Lowest   | default values in `variables.tf` |

